4:38:59 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: If the Bible was written in the 20th century</span><hr size=1> At some point, this thread turned into something akin to those old AOL chat rooms bashing christianity, or promoting Chritiaity, or promoting Evolution, or what have you.  <br>
       When I was younger my faith was tested, to the extreme.  I happended to be in college at the time (hehe i still am btw gradschool though) I searched for answers in Evolution... I believe in Evolution and Creationism  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   I believe God initiated evolution.  I started taking classes in Cosmology.  Cosmology is the study of the beginning of the universe.  I hope you believers of evolution dont mind too much that many prolific cosmologists who can tell you what the universe was like up to .00005 seconds up to the &quot;beginning&quot;, attribute whatever was before this or what ever initiated this, as an act of God.  That was comforting.  To see some of the greatest mathmaticians/physisists relying on God.  <br>
    My point is here that if you are gonna argue science (which is fine because i believe in science) know that at some point, your rationale is based on a cosmic question relying on the act of God.   See, &quot;The Perfect Recipie.&quot; It was an article in a Sky and Telescope magizine by a noted German cosmologist commenting on the 7 Great constants.  Really quickly these constants are things like the atomic wieght of hydrogen, the Quantitative force of gravity, THe universes rate of expansion..etc...etc...etc...  <br>
    If anyone of these numbers was .000000000000000001 different.... well long story short life could not have been possible here or anywhere.. Interesting...  Anyway, the physicist considered the odds of this (universe as we know it's) happening   due to these 7 numbers being precisely what they are is nothing less then Devine Intervention.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Again, to me this lends more Credence to a God.<br>
   As far as the bible, readers can either be (at one end) strict textualists  ... Ie. Adam and eve was the beginning, God created the earth in 7 days (168 hours) Noah in fact did get all the animals and ... etc etc etc...<br>
The other end of the spectrum is Symbolists.  Some catholic priests have even admitted there Symbolists belief of the the Bible.  I am a symbolist.  I believe in the writings of the bible, but again I believe that some of these stories are moral commentaries, or explicative narritives (ie how did universe begin = Book of Genisis).  I believe that there was probably a guy named Noah, he built a boat due to Gods (some devine intervention) wishes, got all the animals he could find around, got his family and whetherd out a monsoon of epic proportions.  I believe in the crossing of the red sea... Note that the red sea (even today) experiences Tidal break flows (water flows out to sea )and lunar tides that cause land bridges to form across its span.  (check my facts, i invite you).. The Nile also experiences abnormal bacteria growth every so often, turning the water undrinkable and blood red in color.       If anything this is food for thought <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
   Concerning Christianity's history.   If you missed it i am Catholic.  The catholic church, for those who dont know, has made formal apologies for their lack of participation in the tragedies of the Holocaust.  As a matter of fact, there was a meeting of the Jewish leaders and the Pope in 1999 (may have been 2000) in which the Pope gave a speech regretting the omissions of the church.  The Jewish leaders accepted the apology and the beliefs have beniffited from it.     <br>
    In responce to the Catholic churches charging for absolution... yeah that was 600 years ago, and I learned about it plenty.  <br>
   As far as the Crusades... it wasnt a fight against Jewish peoples because they refused to convert, The middle east was actually held by the Moors  (muslims) and the fight was to regain the holy city (jeruselam) from a religon (Islam) that had no interest in it, also the crusades were designed to acquire holy relics and artifacts that were held by the Moors.   I lernt about dem too <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
    Note about Riyadd:::   I am catholic and proud.  Its interesting to note how a lot of people who were catholic end up leaving it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   (somehow i am not surprised... catholic school has that effect on folks... (i didnt attend catholic school)) Anyway, I respect all your beliefs... everyone of them.. I sinecerely do... and i simply offer mine, if anything to just show a different perspective.  I am a creature of logic.  Perhaps my tests of faith and my subsequent findings will benefit you... perhaps they may anger you... eitherway i beg all of you to explore your rationale and your underlying arguements... make sure you got resourses striaght <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .  <br>
    If you wanna pro-offer a counter opinion, or a weakness in my logic.. go striaght ahead <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   The more my reasoning is tested, the better.<br>
anyway, i hope this is my last post. (perhaps you do too <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )<br>
-Riy <p><img src=http://www.geocities.com/kiasersozae/riyadd.jpg></br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#292947><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub18.ezboard.com/ufalenesilmarien.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Falene Silmarien</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>MithMarr Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#FF9933>(7/20/01 6:09:03 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://users.ev1.net/~dareid/gbc/sig/minifalene.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: If the Bible was written in the 20th century</span><hr size=1> Saevan, you have again brought to us another thought provoking post.  You seem to have this ability to bring the best and worst out of us, whether we agree with you or not.<br>
<br>
I do not wish to hop too far into this wonderful debate as I am enjoying all of you way too much.<br>
<br>
But I do want to comment on the thoughts about the many that have perished in the name of Christianity/Catholisim and the difficulties minorities face here.<br>
<br>
It is an historical fact that during the end of World War II, the Vatican itself accepted payment from Nazi war criminals to be smuggled out of Europe.  Of course most of this &quot;payment&quot; came from the stolen properties of Jews and any other people who did not agree with Hitler.  In fairness to the Vatican, they also smuggled out Jews, those who could pay the price, which were not many by that time.  I must say that I have a problem with this.  It doesn't seem very Christian to me.<br>
<br>
It is also an historical fact that our country, the United States of America PLANNED the genocide of an entire people...the great tribes that we know as the American Indians.  This plan was based upon the complete extermination of the Plains Buffalo and while not completely successful (the genocide, not the buffalos), came damn close.  Actual documents outlining this plan are on display at the Smithsonian, I believe.  I also have a problem with this.  This doesn't seem like the actions of a country based upon freedom.<br>
<br>
IMHO:<br>
<br>
It is very hard to be Jewish in this country.  It is very hard to be a woman in this country (though we have it a lot better off than in most countries).  It is very hard to be black in this country.  It is very hard to be gay in this country.  It is very hard to be Hispanic in this country.  It seems that if you are not a white, christian male, you may find it hard to live in this country.  I guess it is just hard to be &quot;different&quot;.<br>
<br>
But it IS getting better, everyday.  Yes, we have our fall backs, but we are making progress in the right direction (I hope).<br>
<br>
Be kind to one another.  Be understanding of our differences.  Most importantly, be tolerant of each other.  Try to &quot;love&quot; one another.<br>
<br>
By doing this, you will find heaven on earth......regardless of your beliefs.<br>
<br>
<br>
A Daily Reader of MMDN<br>
<br>
PS-Forgive my spelling mistakes please!<br>
